YVES NAVARRE; AWARD-WINNING FRENCH WRITER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Yves Navarre, 53, one of France's leading contemporary writers. Navarre, who 
had lived for many years in Canada, wrote more than two dozen novels, several 
plays and children's books.Open about his homosexuality, he frequently explored 
the subject in his writings but disliked being described as a homosexual 
writer. In 1991 he wrote a love story dealing with AIDS, "Friends Gone With the 
Wind." Navarre won France's top literary prize, the Goncourt, in 1980 for his 
novel "Le Jardin d'Acclimatation" ("The Zoological Garden"), and in 1992 was 
honored for his body of work by the prestigious French Academy. On Monday in 
Paris, a suicide. 
