<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OJAI; SCHOOL INVESTIGATES ALLEGED RACIAL SLURS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Several girls at Matilija Junior High School in Ojai have been accused of 
making racial slurs against another girl, school officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Principal James Berube said he was investigating a report that someone drew a 
swastika in the dirt near one girl's locker last week and that a racial epithet 
was written on her locker late last month. 
</P>
<P>
 The student, who is black and who transferred into the district in September, 
has also received at least two threatening notes and a series of verbal 
threats, said Lonnie Stanford, the girl's grandfather. 
</P>
<P>
 School officials Tuesday downplayed the incidents, with the principal saying 
it was a dispute over mutual acquaintances. The girls "had been having friend 
problems," Berube said. 
</P>
<P>
 Vice Principal Steve Olsen questioned whether threats were made. 
</P>
<P>
 "The girl said there was something spoken to her as she walked down a sidewalk 
(on campus)," said Olsen, who also is Ojai's mayor. "The other kids 
emphatically denied that it was anything racial." 
</P>
<P>
 Berube said he met with his staff Tuesday to discuss the allegations and said 
he planned to get the parents of the girls together for a meeting with school 
officials. JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
