<TEXT>
<P>
 No Time Warner Board Seat for Seagram: Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin 
indicated that representatives from the Canadian beverage giant won't be 
invited to join the company's board even though Seagram has emerged as Time 
Warner's largest shareholder, with a stake of more than 11%. Time Warner last 
week enacted a so-called poison pill anti-takeover defense after Seagram 
disclosed it had raised its stake.Levin said the Time Warner board will be 
reduced to "10, 11 or 12" members, from about 15 now. Levin said Seagram has 
assured him that the shares were bought for investment purposes, adding that 
